📌 Subject: Follow-Up: Dongguk University’s Gender Policies & Barriers to Reporting Sexual Harassment

Dear Journalists,

I am following up on my previous inquiry regarding Dongguk University’s Graduate School of Digital Image & Contents and the barriers female students face when reporting sexual harassment.

Recent findings raise serious concerns about whether students at Dongguk truly have any means to report harassment, particularly in the Graduate School of Digital Image & Contents, where all faculty members are male (https://www.dongguk.edu/eng/dandae/122#;).

🚨 Contradictory Gender Policies at Dongguk

1️⃣ 2016: Dongguk introduced a policy allowing students to request professor replacements if they suffered verbal or sexual abuse – https://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/2016/08/05/socialAffairs/Dongguk-University-changes-policy-to-help-students-who-suffer-verbal-or-sexual-abuse/3022260.html.

2️⃣ 2018: During the height of the MeToo movement, Dongguk abolished its Women's Student Council, which had previously provided gender advocacy and peer support – https://en.namu.wiki/w/%EB%8F%99%EA%B5%AD%EB%8C%80%ED%95%99%EA%B5%90%20%EC%B4%9D%EC%97%AC%ED%95%99%EC%83%9D%ED%9A%8C%20%ED%8F%90%EC%A7%80%20%EC%82%AC%EA%B1%B4.

3️⃣ 2024: The university’s Graduate School of Digital Image & Contents has no female faculty, raising concerns about how students can report harassment in a department with no gender diversity – https://www.dongguk.edu/eng/dandae/122#;.

These contradictions raise a serious question:
If Dongguk claims to support gender equality, why did it eliminate the very structure that allowed female students to seek help?

📢 International Awareness of the Issue

To escalate the issue, I have already contacted many of Dongguk’s sister universities across Asia, informing them about the potential risks for female exchange students.

International institutions have now been made aware of:

✔ The all-male faculty in Dongguk’s Graduate School of Digital Image & Contents.

✔ The lack of female representation in leadership roles in film academia.

✔ The abolition of the Women’s Student Council in 2018, removing internal student-led gender advocacy.

This raises serious concerns about whether Dongguk students—especially international female students—can safely report misconduct without fear of retaliation.🔍 Next Steps: Investigating the Reality of Reporting at Dongguk

I urge Newstapa & SisaIN to investigate:

📌 Are students aware of the 2016 policy that allows professor replacements? Is it still actively used?

📌 What mechanisms exist for female students to report harassment today?

📌 Have any complaints of harassment at the Graduate School of Digital Image & Contents been reported since 2018?

📌 Why was the Women’s Student Council abolished during MeToo, and has anything replaced it?

📌 What protections exist for international female students who experience harassment?

Dongguk University presents itself as a progressive institution on gender issues, but its actions contradict its public image.

I strongly encourage you to investigate whether students—especially women—actually feel safe coming forward with complaints, or if the removal of the Women’s Student Council and all-male faculty has silenced survivors instead of protecting them.

I appreciate your time and look forward to your response.

